/*!

\page dev_guide_documentation Write documentation for PandA project

Documentation is an essential part of the PandA project.
It explains what the code does, which assumptions a component relies on, and how users or contributors are expected to interact with the implemented functionality.

The documentation of the PandA project is based on Doxygen.
The repository ships a versioned \c documentation/Doxyfile, which is the authoritative starting point for generated project documentation.

\section doc_code_how_to Documenting your Code
Both public-facing documentation and implementation-oriented comments are useful:
- public API documentation explains what a class, method, or data structure means and how it should be used;
- local comments should be reserved for non-obvious implementation details, invariants, or algorithmic choices.

For Doxygen comments in code, keep the style simple and consistent.
The project primarily uses:
-# Documentation of classes and methods must be indicated using Javadoc style
\verbatim
/**
 * ....your documentation.....
 */
\endverbatim
-# Documentation of class attributes is indicated in a C# style:
\verbatim
///......your documentation....
\endverbatim
Place these comments immediately before the declaration they describe.

Documentation should be specific and useful:
- \b Classes should explain the role of the abstraction and the responsibility it owns.
- \b Attributes should explain what state they represent when that meaning is not obvious from the name alone.
- \b Methods should document parameters, return values, preconditions, postconditions, and externally visible side effects when relevant.
- Prefer documenting invariants, ownership rules, and error conditions over repeating what is already obvious from the signature.

Regarding inline comments inside the implementation, ordinary source comments are enough:
\verbatim
//......comment.......
\endverbatim
Use them sparingly and only when they add information that the code structure itself does not already communicate.

\section ext_docs_how_to Writing External Documentation Pages
Standalone documentation pages are useful for workflows, subsystem overviews, and contributor guidance that do not fit well in API comments.
Keep these pages close to the code or assets they describe, and prefer concise pages with stable guidance over long step-by-step procedures that are likely to go stale.

PandA also uses conditional Doxygen sections for documentation that should only appear when a given project area is enabled. Use the existing section conventions already present in the tree when you need this behavior, for example:
\verbatim
\if BAMBU
.....documentation about the BAMBU project.....
\endif
\endverbatim

\section doc_compilation_how_to Compiling the Documentation
The repository provides a versioned Doxygen configuration in \c documentation/Doxyfile.
Use the documentation command exposed by your configured build tree when available, or invoke Doxygen directly with that file if you are working on the documentation setup itself.

When updating these pages:
- prefer references to checked-in files over references to external websites;
- avoid hard-coding version matrices or host-specific package lists unless they are actively maintained;
- remove or rewrite pages whose main content is no longer aligned with the current repository layout or build flow.
*/
